[2] Malaysia - virus serotypes
Date: 11 Jan 2007
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: New Straits Times - Persekutuan,Malaysia, 11 Jan 2007, [edited]
<http://www.nst.com.my/Current_News/nst/Thursday/National/20070111083825/Article/local1_html>

Two deadlier forms of dengue virus have resurfaced in Malaysia, which
could mean a higher death toll in 2007, says a dengue expert. The
resurgence is why doctors are seeing patients with the more severe
form of dengue fever, said University Malaya Medical Centre's Prof Dr
Sazaly Abu Bakar. "This year, we have been seeing predominantly the
Den-2 and Den-3 viruses (in samples sent for testing)," said the head
of the UMMC's medical microbiology department.
Suspected dengue cases have risen by 1/3 to 1155 in the 1st week this
year [2007], from 865 in mid-November [2006], and health authorities
are bracing themselves for more.
Den-2 and Den-3 are 2 of the 4 viruses that cause dengue and dengue
haemorrhagic fever. And these 2 viruses have a particularly bad
effect on those who have survived dengue fever caused by Den-1,
another form of the virus. Immunity from one virus does not confer
immunity from the other 3.
While Den-1 is endemic to Malaysia, the incidence of Den-2 and Den-3
occurs in cycles. Den-2 last struck in 1998/99 and Den-3 in 2003.
Den-3 is expected to gain dominance over Den-2 in 2008/9, said Dr
Sazaly. Den-4 has lost the predominance it had in the '60s and '70s.
Malaysia had not yet been struck by Den-4 [this year], he added.
Detection had improved with 2 new techniques that identify dengue
antigens within a day, he said.
Known as Dengue NS1 and PCR molecular detection, each test costs
between RM30 and RM60, and is available in some private hospitals.
The conventional test works only 4-6 days after the 1st symptoms
appear. "It is better if people can get their results on the 1st day
of symptoms so that appropriate measures can be taken to stop or
reduce the spread of the disease," he added.
[Byline: Annie Freeda Cruez]
