[4] Indonesia - earthquake effects
Date: 11 Jan 2007
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Jakarta Post - Jakarta,Indonesia, 11 Jan 2007 [edited]
<http://www.thejakartapost.com/detailnational.asp?fileid=20070111.G02&irec=1>

Multiple cases of dengue fever have been reported in Yogyakarta,
where one person has died so far.
The Bantul Health and Communicable Diseases Handling Office said it
did not have concrete data on infection numbers. "Based on our data
only 2 people were infected, including the person who passed away,"
the office's head, Maya Sintawa, said Tuesday.
The office's data contradicts the number of hospital patients with
symptoms of the disease, however, with 4 patients treated at
Panembahan Senopati Hospital alone.
Maya said areas affected by the 27 May 2006 earthquake were prone to
the outbreak of disease. "Debris from damaged houses and other
buildings are favorable breeding grounds for mosquitoes," she said.
Many earthquake survivors have been forced to live in makeshift
shelters and tents, leaving them exposed to disease-carrying insects
such as mosquitoes.
Data at the Bantul Health Office showed that following the May
earthquake the number of people suffering from dengue fever jumped by
290, up to 498. Six of these died as a result of the disease. Four
deaths were recorded from 208 reported infections in 2005.
In efforts to prevent the disease from spreading, the Bantul Health
Office has launched an initiative on Dec. 29 [2006], to eradicate
mosquitoes. "Such a movement is considered the most effective means
of fighting further outbreaks," Maya said. Maya further urged
residents to immediately send children with symptoms of dengue fever
to the hospital. "Don't wait, or sufferers may not survive," she said.
The Yogyakarta mayoralty has donated one ton of anti-larva abate
powder to local residents to help prevent future dengue outbreaks.
The powder is being distributed from community health centers
throughout the city's 17 districts.
[Byline: Slamet Susanto]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[It is tragic enough that the earthquake victims suffered so much
from that event, and more so now that they are living in damaged
housing or temporary shelters that provide breeding sites for _Aedes_
dengue virus vectors. - Mod.TY]
